      "url": "https://perc.tamu.edu/blog/2023/08/wind-and-solar-energy-in-texas.html",
      "title": "Wind and Solar Energy in Texas",
      "published_date": "2023-08-01T00:00:00.000Z",
      "text": "Wind and Solar Energy in Texas\n\nThe dashboard displays the location of wind power turbines as provided in the U.S. Wind Turbine Database (USWTDB) by the United States Geological Survey (USGS), the American Clean Power Association, and the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory. (See https://eerscmap.usgs.gov/uswtdb.)\n\nBy zooming in to a point on the map, the exact locations of individual wind turbines are denoted with a dot. The associated pop up displays the attributes of each individual turbine. By hovering over the points in the map, the panel on the right titled Wind Power Project Attributes by Project Name and Year Online displays the information about the county in which the turbine is located, the number of turbines in each project, the year it went online, the project capacity, and the hub height of the turbines in that county. Hub height or turbine tower is the distance from the ground to the middle of the turbine’s rotor. Taller turbine towers along with larger rotor blades help capture more energy, as winds become free from obstacles high above the ground. Almost all of the taller turbines are located in the North Central Plains and Great Plains of Texas. Texas leads the U.S. in wind power generation. The graph labeled Trend of Turbines and Turbine Capacity shows the cumulative installed turbine capacity and the cumulative number of turbines over the years 1999 to 2023. The number of turbines and the installed capacities for wind energy show a sharply increasing trend line from 2007 onwards. The major increase in the number of turbines was between 2016 and 2017 with the addition of 1,871 turbines. As of May 2023, the total installed capacity is slightly above 39,000MW. To note, installed capacity of a turbine is the maximum energy capacity a turbine can reach if it operates full time at rated power. The power system in the United States is interconnected via a large network of power lines and equipment that can move electric power between Western, Eastern and Texas Interconnections. The transmission grid that provides electricity to most of Texas is within the Texas Interconnection and is called the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT). Figure 1 illustrates the ERCOT Load Zone Map which covers all but a small part of Texas. Source: Electric Reliability Council of Texas, developed by PERC The combined contribution of wind and solar energy based on 2022 ERCOT data averaged 30%, of which 25% was contributed by wind and the rest by solar. Wind production varies on an intraday basis and on a seasonal basis. The seasonal variation in the contributions of wind and solar power to ERCOT power production can be seen in the chart below. March and April provided the highest percentage of wind power while June, July and August produced the least. Source: Electric Reliability Council of Texas Figure 2 depicts the seasonal variation of the wind and solar power generation. Note that the highest wind generation months do not coincide with the months of highest demand for electricity, which are typically the months of June, July, and August as shown in the figure below. Compiling data for the months from the latest available ERCOT data from 2020 through 2022, average wind power generation in March, April, and May was 33.6%, 32.7%, and 28.9%, respectively, of the total power production in those months. However, average wind power generation in June, July, and August was 21.7%, 16.7%, and 16.1%, respectively, of the total power production in those months. This volatility in power production occurs in part because average wind speed varies by month, and also because total power demand, and production, is higher in summer months. It also varies by geographic region. Solar power generation has increased from 3.9% of total power production in 2021 to 5.5% in 2022, contributing to an expanding footprint of renewable energy in Texas. In Figure 3, the monthly ERCOT load (left axis) and monthly total wind power generation (right axis) are graphed for a three year period beginning in December 2019. Wind power generation was at a maximum of 12,455,853 MW in May 2022. (Note that installed capacity at that time was over 39,000,000 MW.) The previous figure indicated that, in May 2022, wind power generation was just over 32% of ERCOT load. Then just a few months later, wind power production was 5,741,858 MW. Even in its best month, production from wind turbines is far below the rated installed capacity as wind speeds vary. To match energy generation with the demand for electricity throughout the year, a mix of natural gas, coal, nuclear and other resources are used alongside wind and solar. Figure 4 shows the fuel combination used by ERCOT to meet the electricity demand in the period May 2022 to May 2023. Over this period, 44.1% of the electricity demand across Texas was met by natural gas, followed by wind at around 25.3%, coal at 14.9%, nuclear at 9.4%, solar at 6.1%, and other comprises 0.2%. Source: Electricity Reliability Council of Texas There are fundamental limitations, and challenges, with incorporating electricity generation by wind and sun, as these are governed by the seasonal and diurnal variations. Texas, and ERCOT, have demonstrated that wind and solar power can make a large manageable contribution to power production and to the growing energy needs of the state.",
      "highlights": [
        "However, average wind power generation in June, July, and August was 21.7%, 16.7%, and 16.1%, respectively, of the total power production in those months. This volatility in power production occurs in part because average wind speed varies by month, and also because total power demand, and production, is higher in summer months. It also varies by geographic region. Solar power generation has increased from 3.9% of total power production in 2021 to 5.5% in 2022, contributing to an expanding footprint of renewable energy in Texas. In Figure 3, the monthly ERCOT load (left axis) and monthly total wind power generation (right axis) are graphed for a three year period beginning in December 2019. Wind power generation was at a maximum of 12,455,853 MW in May 2022. (Note that installed capacity at that time was over 39,000,000 MW.) The previous figure indicated that, in May 2022, wind power generation was just over 32% of ERCOT load. Then just a few months later, wind power production was 5,741,858 MW. Even in its best month, production from wind turbines is far below the rated installed capacity as wind speeds vary. To match energy generation with the demand for electricity throughout the year, a mix of natural gas, coal, nuclear and other resources are used alongside wind and solar. Figure 4 shows the fuel combination used by ERCOT to meet the electricity demand in the period May 2022 to May 2023. Over this period, 44.1% of the electricity demand across Texas was met by natural gas, followed by wind at around 25.3%, coal at 14.9%, nuclear at 9.4%, solar at 6.1%, and other comprises 0.2%. Source: Electricity Reliability Council of Texas There are fundamental limitations, and challenges, with incorporating electricity generation by wind and sun, as these are governed by the seasonal and diurnal variations. Texas, and ERCOT, have demonstrated that wind and solar power can make a large manageable contribution to power production and to the growing energy needs of the state."
      ]
    }
  ]
}",
