      "text": "## Fact Sheet\n\nMay 2026\n\nThe Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) is a nonprofit organization that ensures reliable electric service for 90 percent of the state of Texas. The grid operator is regulated by the Public Utility Commission of Texas and the Texas Legislature.\n\n1,928+ active market participants that generate, move, buy, sell or use wholesale electricity\n\n90% percent of Texas Load\n\n1,460+ generating units, including PUNs\n\n55,000+ miles of high-voltage transmission\n\nMore than 27 million customers in the ERCOT region\n\n104,850+ MW expected capacity for Summer 2026 peak demand (December 2025 CDR)\n\n40,719 MW\n\n75% of load is competitive-choice customers — nearly 8 million electric-service IDs (premises)\n\nof installed wind capacity as of March 2026, the most of any state in the nation\n\n1 MW of electricity is enough to serve about 250 residential customers during ERCOT peak hours.\n\n37,824 MW of utility-scale installed solar capacity as of March 2026\n\n85,116 MW Weekend peak demand record (Aug 20, 2023)\n\n85,508 MW Record peak demand (Aug 10, 2023)\n\n18,795 MW of installed energy storage as of March 2026\n\n29,011 MW wind generation record (May 18, 2026)\n\n| 2026 Generating Capacity Reflects operational installed capacity for Summer 2026 based on | | | 0.1% Other* 8.6% Storage | | |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| December 2025 CDR report. | | | 2.9% Nuclear | | |\n| Natural Gas 37.5% | Wind 22.4% | Coal 7.6% | Solar 19.7% | | |\n\n0.3% Hydro\n\n69.15% wind penetration record (Apr 10, 2022)\n\n34,498 MW solar generation record (May 13, 2026)\n\nThe sum of the percentages may not equal 100% due to rounding. \n*Other includes biomass and DC Tie capacity. \n\n#### 2025 Energy Use\n\n72.74% solar penetration record (May 2, 2026)\n\n25.2.%\n\n*Other includes solar, hydro, petroleum coke (pet coke), biomass, landfill gas, distillate fuel oil, net DC-tie and Block Load Transfer imports/exports and an adjustment for wholesale storage load.\n\n-0.1% Other* 8.6% Nuclear\n\nNatural Gas 45.1%\n\nWind 24.3%\n\nNatural Gas Wind 23.6%\n\nCoal 12.9%\n\nSolar 41.1% 13.9%\n\n$14 billion transmission projects endorsed in 2025\n\n### ERCOT Board of Directors\n\n### ERCOT Executive Team\n\n### Download the ERCOT app\n\nERCOT.com x.com/ercot_iso instagram.com/ercot_iso facebook.com/ERCOTISO/ linkedin.com/company/ercot\n\n### Connect with us\n\nPablo Vegas\n\nJayapal Parakkuth Senior Vice President and Chief Digital Officer\n\nWoody Rickerson\n\nSenior Vice President, Chief Financial Officer and Chief Risk Officer\n\nRichard L. Scheel\n\nChad V. Seely\n\nVice President, Chief Information Security Officer\n\nKristi Hobbs\n\nAdam Martinez\n\nVenkat Tirupati\n\nDan Woodfin\n\nBryan Hanley\n\nJeff Billo\n\nDrew Bonser\n\nMaintain system reliability. \nFacilitate a competitive \nwholesale market. \nFacilitate a competitive \nretail market. \nEnsure open access to \ntransmission. \n\nIn 1999, the Texas Legislature restructured the Texas electric market and assigned ERCOT four primary responsibilities:\n\nERCOT manages the flow of electric power to more than 27 million Texas customers, representing about 90 percent of the state’s electric load. As the Independent System Operator for the region, ERCOT schedules power on an electric grid that connects more than 55,000+ miles of transmission lines and 1,460 generation units, including Private Use Networks. ERCOT also performs financial settlement for the competitive wholesale bulk-power market and administers retail switching for more than 8 million premises in competitive choice areas. ERCOT is a membership-based 501(c)(4) nonprofit corporation, governed by a board of directors and subject to oversight by the Public Utility Commission of Texas and the Texas Legislature.\n\nPublic Utility Commssion of Texas\n\nTechnical Advisory Committee\n\nStakeholder Subcommittees\n\nState Leadership Texas Legislature\n\nERCOT Board of Directors\n\nMay 2026\n\nBill Flores Chair - Director\n\nPeggy Heeg Vice Chair - Director\n\nBenjamin Barkley Public Counsel\n\nLinda Capuano Director\n\nJulie England Director\n\nThomas Gleeson Chair of PUCT\n\nCourtney Hjaltman Commissioner, PUCT\n\nChristopher A. Krummel Director\n\nKathleen McAllister Public Counsel\n\nBill Mohl Director\n\nJohn Swainson Director\n\nPablo Vegas President and Chief Executive Officer\n\nVice President, Interconnection and Grid Analysis\n\nSenior Vice President and Chief Operating Officer\n\nSenior Vice President, Regulatory Policy, General Counsel, Chief Compliance Officer, and Corporate Secretary\n\nVice President, System Operations\n\nVice President, Chief Technology Officer\n\nVice President, Enterprise Risk and Strategy\n\nVice President, DevOps and Architecture\n\nAjay Mannepalli\n\nVice President, System Planning and Weatherization\n\nVice President, IT Infrastructure\n\nPresident and Chief Executive Officer\n\nBrandon Gleason Vice President, Legal and Compliance, and Assistant Corporate Secretary\n\nKeith Collins Vice President, Commercial Operations\n\n",
